TY  - JOUR
T1  - Intellectual Property Strategy and the Long Tail: Evidence from the Recorded Music Industry
AU  - Zhang, Laurina
Y1  - 2016/11/11
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2018/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2016.2562
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2016.2562
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 24
EP  - 42
VL  - 64
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Digitization has impacted firm profitability in many media industries by lowering the cost of copying and sharing creative works. I examine the impact of digital rights management (DRM), a prevalent strategy used by firms in media industries to address piracy concerns, on music sales. I exploit a natural experiment, where different labels remove DRM from their entire catalogue of music at different times, to examine whether relaxing an album?s sharing restrictions increases sales. Using a large sample of albums from all four major record labels, I find that removing DRM increases digital music sales by 10%, but relaxing sharing restrictions does not impact all albums equally. It increases the sales of lower-selling albums (i.e., the ?long tail?) significantly (40%) but does not benefit top-selling albums. These results suggest that reducing search costs facilitates the discovery of niche products. This paper was accepted by Lee Fleming, entrepreneurship and innovation.
AB  - Digitization has impacted firm profitability in many media industries by lowering the cost of copying and sharing creative works. I examine the impact of digital rights management (DRM), a prevalent strategy used by firms in media industries to address piracy concerns, on music sales. I exploit a natural experiment, where different labels remove DRM from their entire catalogue of music at different times, to examine whether relaxing an album?s sharing restrictions increases sales. Using a large sample of albums from all four major record labels, I find that removing DRM increases digital music sales by 10%, but relaxing sharing restrictions does not impact all albums equally. It increases the sales of lower-selling albums (i.e., the ?long tail?) significantly (40%) but does not benefit top-selling albums. These results suggest that reducing search costs facilitates the discovery of niche products. This paper was accepted by Lee Fleming, entrepreneurship and innovation.
SN  - 0025-1909
M3  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2016.2562
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2016.2562
Y2  - 2024/03/29
