TY  - JOUR
T1  - Making Sense of (Ultra) Low-Cost Flights Vertical Differentiation in Two-Sided Markets
AU  - Serio, Luigi
AU  - Tedeschi, Piero
AU  - Ursino, Giovanni
Y1  - 2016/12/16
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2018/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2016.2601
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2016.2601
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 401
EP  - 420
VL  - 64
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The business model of low-cost carriers is now well established and accounts for a large share of Western civil aviation, particularly in Europe. To understand why it has proven so successful, we develop a theoretical model that exploits the two-sided nature of flights as connectors of supply and demand for goods and services other than traveling itself across physical space. Carriers offer flights of different quality and may sign agreements with suppliers of goods and services at the destination so as to subsidize and foster demand from the carriers? travelers as in standard two-sided markets. Customers/travelers care about home and destination consumption and about the flight?s quality. Hence, beyond the thickness of the connected sides of the market, the quality of the airline platform has an intrinsic value to travelers. We show that only low-income travelers fly with low-cost airlines, while no-frills carriers are more likely to act as a platform than legacy airlines. We study how the degree of substitution between home and destination consumption affects the equilibrium market structure of the airline industry. This paper was accepted by Bruno Cassiman, business strategy.
AB  - The business model of low-cost carriers is now well established and accounts for a large share of Western civil aviation, particularly in Europe. To understand why it has proven so successful, we develop a theoretical model that exploits the two-sided nature of flights as connectors of supply and demand for goods and services other than traveling itself across physical space. Carriers offer flights of different quality and may sign agreements with suppliers of goods and services at the destination so as to subsidize and foster demand from the carriers? travelers as in standard two-sided markets. Customers/travelers care about home and destination consumption and about the flight?s quality. Hence, beyond the thickness of the connected sides of the market, the quality of the airline platform has an intrinsic value to travelers. We show that only low-income travelers fly with low-cost airlines, while no-frills carriers are more likely to act as a platform than legacy airlines. We study how the degree of substitution between home and destination consumption affects the equilibrium market structure of the airline industry. This paper was accepted by Bruno Cassiman, business strategy.
